node.text: Today is my final day at NASA and the start of my retirement from the Navy.  It’s been such an honor to serve our nation - wearing my uniform and wearing a space suit!  #gratitude #thankful #neutralbuoyancylaboratory #nbl @nasaastronauts @nasa @usnavy @usnavalacademy @navalspecialwarfare

Always so super cool to watch a crew walk out in space suits and begin the trip to the launch pad!  This was the scene early this morning as we cheered on #spacex #crew2 getting in the #tesla  @astro_kimbrough @astro.megan @thom_astro #akihoshide

node.text: @nasaastronauts having a few laughs in the #iss mock-up!  During the last week of training in Houston prior to launch each crew typically meets with a recently returned crew to discuss the latest status of things on the station.  Today it was a special treat for @astrodrewmorgan and me to cover a few topics with the #spacexdragon #crew2  I haven’t yet seen any of them since returning from space in October, so prior to the class, Drew and I surprised them with “biological payload” hidden in a cargo bag!  Lots of good laughs and wonderful to see my friends and colleagues again!  @astro_kimbrough @astro.megan @astrodrewmorgan @thom_astro

node.text: After returning from space flight our bodies need some help getting readjusted to gravity.  We have three “ASCRs” (Astronaut Strength Conditioning and Rehabilitation  specialists), and I have worked with Staci before, during, and after this mission. Today was a big day because we just wrapped up the whole process with a “functional fitness test”. Thanks to Staci, I’m happy to say all of my numbers have returned to, or exceeded, pre-flight tests.  Thank you, Staci, #yourock !!
